															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tunedtoadeadchannel" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(304457); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=304457&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252558" alt="tunedtoadeadchannel" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=304457)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tunedtoadeadchannel" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(304457); return false;" >tunedtoadeadchannel</a></span> <span class="odate time_1329374437 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">16 Feb 2012 06:40</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1375321">
									

<p>From what I've always seen in tales, the proper form is &quot;Ess See Pee&quot;, and the abbreviated &quot;skips&quot; is generally used by rough and tumble agent types.</p>
<p>I'd imagine the use depends entirely on the situation; in casual discussion, &quot;skips&quot; or &quot;scips&quot; is fine, but if you called them that while, say, recording your official research notes for a thesis you intend to present to a superior, you'd look like a jackass and probably be reprimanded.</p>
<p>Either way, I don't like the line in the story, which presents a casual abbreviation as official policy.</p>

							</div>

								
					
